So that the PHP code gives the same ciphertext as the Java code, the following is necessary:

- In `encrypt()`, the determination of the HMAC and the concatenation have to be removed, since neither happens in the Java code.

- Instead, `$ciphertext_raw` must be returned (where `$ciphertext_raw` is an odd name, since `openssl_encrypt()` returns the ciphertext Base64 encoded by default).

- The key to be passed to `encrypt()` is to be determined with `derivate_key()`. Note that `$keyLengthBits` and the algorithm must be consistent, e.g. for an n bit key AES-n-CBC must be specified.

Then, if the same values for password, salt, iteration count, and key size are used for both codes, both codes will return the same ciphertext. 

Full code and example: 

```php
&lt;?php
function derivate_key($password, $salt, $iterations, $keyLengthBits): string {
    return hash_pbkdf2(&quot;sha256&quot;, $password, $salt, $iterations, $keyLengthBits / 8, true);
}

function encrypt($plaintext, $key): string {
    $iv = str_repeat(chr(0), 16);
    $cipher = &quot;AES-256-CBC&quot;;
    $ciphertext_raw = openssl_encrypt($plaintext, $cipher, $key, 0, $iv);
    //$hmac = hash_hmac(&quot;sha256&quot;, $ciphertext_raw, $key, true);
    //return base64_encode($iv . $hmac . $ciphertext_raw);
    return $ciphertext_raw;
}

$salt = &quot;This is a test salt&quot;;
$password = &quot;This is a test Passphrase&quot;;
$iterations = 10000;
$keyLengthBits = 256;

$key = derivate_key($password, $salt, $iterations, $keyLengthBits);
$ciphertext = encrypt(&quot;The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog&quot;, $key);
print($ciphertext . PHP_EOL); // cqSHCSOOZlZmugahBVpTusElSEN1gKqiQQDUr1YF1AlLAO466g1/DldwcuoWOjOW
?&gt;
```

which produces the same (Bas64 encoded) ciphertext as the Java code:

```none
cqSHCSOOZlZmugahBVpTusElSEN1gKqiQQDUr1YF1AlLAO466g1/DldwcuoWOjOW
```

-------------

Security:
 
It looks like you are using a static salt. A static salt is generally problematic (see e.g. [here][1]). Because of the static IV there is an additional problem: Since a static salt always generates the same key for the same password, key/IV pairs are reused, which is also insecure (for some algorithms like CTR or GCM even fatal).

For this reason, a random salt of sufficient length should be generated for each encryption here (and in general). The random salt generates different keys, so that even with a static IV there is no reuse of key/IV pairs. The salt is not secret and is passed along with the ciphertext to the decrypting side, typically concatenated. 

If you want to avoid the dependence of the IV on the randomness of the salt, the IV can also be generated randomly. The IV is also not secret and is passed together with the salt and ciphertext to the decrypting side, also concatenated.&lt;br&gt;

On the decrypting side the parts can be separated using the known lengths for salt and/or IV.

[1]: https://dchest.com/2020/06/15/does-salt-need-to-be-random-for-password-hashing/

